ame_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toPachai Vilakku(link changed toPachai Vilakku (1964 film)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Viswanathan%E2%80%93Ramamoorthy"}
{"title_page": "James Playfair (businessman)", "text_new": "{{About|the Canadian businessperson|the Scottish architect|James Playfair}}\n\n{{infobox person\n|name=James Playfair\n|birth_date=8 July 1860\n|birth_place=[[Toronto]], [[Ontario]]\n|death_date={{death date and age|1937|05|25|1860|9|27|df=y}}\n|death_place=[[Midland, Ontario]], Canada\n|known_for=Great Lakes shipping; Midland businessman\n|occupation=Businessman\n|relations=\n|spouse=Charlotte Ogilivie\n}}\n\n'''James Playfair''' (8 July 1860 \u2013 25 May 1937) was noted for his entrepreneurship in the Great Lakes shipping, lumbering, grain handling, and industrial manufacturing businesses. He was a central figure in the establishment of [[Midland, Ontario]], Canada. The son of John Speirs Playfair (26 June 1826, Glasgow \u2013 2 June 1913, Toronto) and Georgina Hall of Montreal, in 1889 Playfair married Sarah Charlotte Ogilvie (1858-1945), youngest daughter of Senator [[Alexander Walker Ogilvie|A.W. Ogilvie]] of Montreal, former president of Ogilvie Flour Mills.\n\n==Lumbering==\nAt the age of 19, James Playfair was hired by the Toronto Lumber Company which had timber holdings in Simcoe County and mills at Collingwood.<ref>Toronto Marine Historical Society, Scanner, February 1979</ref> The lumbering firm of James Playfair & Company was started in 1884.<ref>The Canada Lumberman magazine, November 1896</ref> Playfair's first mill was located at Sturgeon Bay, (between Waubaushene and Victoria Harbour).<ref>The Canada Lumberman magazine June 15, 1885</ref> In 1894 he formed a lumber partnership with Douglas Leyland White, Jr. and together they purchased the mill formerly known as the [[Andrew Miscampbell|Miscampbell]] mill, at Midland.<ref>The Canada Lumberman magazine, November 1894</ref> D. L. White Jr. of Saginaw, Michigan, was the former treasurer of the Emery Lumber Co. of Saginaw and East Tawas, MI. incorporated in 1885. They were involved in the export of logs from the Sudbury region, to supply their Michigan mills. When the export duty on logs was increased in 1886, the vice president of the Emery Lumber Co. [[Ralph A. Loveland|R. A. Loveland]] arranged to have that firm's Georgian Bay logs manufactured into lumber at Miscampbell's mill.<ref>The Canada Lumberman magazine, October 1887</ref> By the 1890's Andrew Miscampbell desired to devote more of his time to politics. He sold his mill to the Emery Lumber Co. in 1891, but with the reduction of the duty on logs exported to the United States, operations of the Midland mill were abandoned and Emery's lumber production was resumed on the American side.<ref>The Canada Lumberman magazine, May 1891</ref> D. L. White Jr. continued his involvement with the Saginaw Lumber And Salt Company (incorporated in 1881), with the same officers as the Emery Lumber Co.<ref>The Canada Lumberman magazine, February 1893</ref> With their acquisition of the former Emery Lumber Co. mill, James Playfair and D. L. White formed the Playfair-White Company. They contracted to supply the lumber requirements of Saginaw lumberman Arthur Hill, with logs from timber limits the French and Spanish rivers. The mill operated at full capacity until 1916, when the Midland Shipbuilding Company was established on the same site.<ref>Midland on Georgian Bay, (an Illustrated History of Midland, Ontario) by William Northcott and William Smith, published by Huronia Museum, Midland. 2008</ref>\n\n==Shipping Interests==\nIn 1895, Playfair purchased from Burton Bros., of Collingwood, the tug [[Metamora (tug)|METAMORA]], three barges and a large quantity of boom logs, which he planned to use in connection with the lumbering business.<ref>The Canada Lumberman magazine February 1895</ref> In partnership with [[John Waldie]] and Capt. W. H. Featherstonhaugh, Playfair purchased an 11 year old steamer, the W. B. HALL in 1896. The ship was lengthened at the [[Polson Iron Works Limited|Polson Shipyard]] at [[Owen Sound]], renamed ST. ANDREW, and placed in the grain trade between  [[Fort William, Ontario|Fort William]] and [[Goderich, Ontario|Goderich]].<ref>The Midland Navigation Company Limited A Short Corporate History and Vessel Listing, Scanner, v. 11, n. 5, February 1979</ref> The tug, METAMORA and barge ST. ANDREW, were operated by Playfair's Barge And Tug Line.<ref>Official Directory and Atlas of Grand Trunk Railway System 1897-1898</ref> The ST. ANDREW served Playfair for five seasons but, on September 20, 1900, she stranded on an island on [[Lake Superior]] and became a total loss.<ref>Scanner, v. 11, n. 5, February 1979</ref> The METAMORA along with other ships MAGNOLIA, RELIANCE and TRAVELER became part of the Midland Towing And Wrecking Co. Ltd.<ref>The Railway And Marine World magazine, May 1907</ref> The METAMORA struck a shoal at Shawanaga Bay, near Parry Sound in 1907. It subsequently caught fire and was completely destroyed.<ref>The Railway And Marine World magazine, November 1907</ref> \n\nPlayfair incorporated the Midland Navigation Company, in 1901. The Steel bulk carrier MIDLAND QUEEN was built in 1901 at Dundee, Scotland. A second vessel, the MIDLAND KING, was a steel bulk carrier built 1903 at Collingwood by Collingwood Shipbuilding Co. Ltd. The steel bulk carrier MIDLAND PRINCE, was built 1906-07 by Collingwood Shipbuilding Co. EMPRESS OF MIDLAND built in 1907 and the EMPRESS OF FORT WILLIAM built 1908, were steel bulk carriers, both built at Wallsend-on-Tyne by Swan Hunter & Wigham Richardson Ltd. the latter two vessels built for the Midland Navigation Co., but soon became part of the Empress Navigation Co. of Midland.<ref>Scanner, v. 11, n. 5, February 1979</ref>\n\nIn March, 1910, Playfair and Company gained control of the Inland Navigation Company Ltd. from the Mackay brothers, of Hamilton.<ref>Ship of the Month No. 96 WAHCONDAH, Scanner, v. 13, n. 2 November 1980.</ref> A plan was devised to merge the company with the Midland Navigation Co. and the Empress Navigation Co. The ships of the Hamilton firm were: NEEPAWAH, WAHCONDAH, ROSEDALE, GLENELLAH, DUNDEE, DUNELM, WINONA, STRATHCONA, DONNACONA, DUNDURN and STADACONA. The new company was incorporated as Inland Lines Ltd.<ref>The Railway And Marine World magazine, June 1910</ref> \n\nIn mid-January 1911, James Playfair made a bid to purchase the Northern Navigation Co. on behalf of himself and his associates. The offer to purchase the company was subject to approval by the Grand Trunk Railway, concerning a previous arrangement that its president C. M. Hays had made with the company for the construction of a new steamship of the HAMONIC type. The conditions were met and James Playfair became the new president of Northern Navigation Co.<ref>The Railway And Marine World magazine, March 1911</ref> While a merger between the Northern Navigation Co. and Inland Lines Ltd. had been discussed, it was thought that a holding company to control them, was more probable. At that time, there was talk of an even larger merger between the Northern Navigation Co. and the Richelieu And Ontario Navigation Co.<ref>The Railway And Marine World magazine, April 1911.</ref> In 1911 the  Richelieu And Ontario Navigation Co. were allowed to increase their capital stock. At a special meeting of shareholders held on June 26, it was decided to increase the stock from $ 5,000,0000 to $ 10,000,000, with the distribution of new shares to be issued by the directors. The shares of the Northern Navigation Co. Ltd. and of the Inland Lines Ltd. were purchased and paid for with fully paid up stock of the R. And O Navigation Co. Five additional directors were added to the reorganized Richelieu And Ontario Navigation Co. James Playfair became the vice president and managing director.<ref>The Railway And Marine World magazine, July 1911</ref>\n\nOn June 2, 1913, James Playfair was on his way to [[Thunder Bay, Ontario|Port Arthur]], for the launching of the [[SS Noronic|NORONIC]]. He was a passenger on the [[Hamonic (steamship)|HAMONIC]] somewhere on Lake Superior, when the [[wireless]] operator received word that James' father, had passed away in [[Toronto]]. 87 year old John S. Playfair, came to Canada as an employee of dry goods merchant [[John McMurrich]]. For some time John Playfair had managed the firm's Kingston store and may have been involved with shipping on Lake Ontario. He first became involved with [[Alexander Peter Cockburn|A. P. Cockburn]]'s Muskoka Lakes Navigation Co. in 1879 and served as president of that line for more than 25 years. James Playfair transferred to one of the R And O Nav. Co. freighters mid-lake, about 80 miles from [[Sault Ste. Marie, Ontario|Sault Ste. Marie]] and made his way to Toronto by special train.<ref>Canadian Railway And Marine World magazine, July 1913</ref> <ref>Dictionary of Canadian Biography/McMURRICH, JOHN</ref>\n\nA special meeting of the shareholders of Richelieu And Ontario Navigation Co. was held in the company's office in Montreal, on June 19, to ratify an agreement of sale of the company's assets to a new company formed for that purpose. The new company was to be called Canada Transportation Lines Limited.<ref>Canadian Railway And Marine World magazine, July July 1913</ref> In the early part of December it was announced that Canada Transportation Lines would be renamed [[Canada Steamship Lines|Canada Steamship Lines Limited]].<ref>Canadian Railway And Marine World magazine, December 1913</ref> With the acquisition of Inland Lines Ltd. by Canada Transportation Lines, Playfair relinquished personal control of his ships, although he was still a director of the company. James Playfair retired as managing director early in 1914. At Toronto, Playfair was presented with a solid silver center table piece and rose bowl with the following inscription: \"Presented to James Playfair by the officials, staff, captains and engineers of the Inland Lines, Ltd., and Northern Navigation Co., Ltd., as a token of the high esteem in which he is held by one and all.\" An old English chime clock was also presented to Mrs. Playfair.<ref>Canadian Railway And Marine World magazine, March 1914</ref>\n\n==A New Beginning==\nAll aforementioned ships of Inland Lines Ltd. were taken over by the R And O Navigation Co. and absorbed into the new Canada Steamship Lines in 1913. \nIn 1914, Playfair and Company, incorporated the Great Lakes Transportation Company Ltd., to carry on a general navigation business.<ref>Canadian Railway And Marine World magazine, May 1914</ref>  Two of the first ships operated by this firm were the GLENMAVIS and the GLENFOYLE reported to have been built for Playfair interests at [[Derry|Londonderry]], Ireland,<ref>Canadian Railway And Marine World magazine, September and October 1913</ref> Both were owned by James Richardson and Sons, of Kingston Ont. and later operated by Great Lakes Transportation Co. along with the CALGARY built at [[Newcastle upon Tyne|Newcastle]] in 1912.<ref>Maritime History of the Great Lakes website</ref> Playfair soon began to rebuild his own fleet of steamships, from the Pittsburgh Steamship Co. he purchased the WAWATAM, renamed GLENLIVET and from the Chicago and Duluth Transportation Co., came the MINNEKAHTA and MINNETONKA, renamed GLENLYON and GLENFINNAN. The motor vessel TOILER was also acquired, but soon resold.<ref>Canadian Railway And Marine World magazine, April 1914</ref> \n\nThe Glen Transportation Co. Ltd. was incorporated in 1920, the purpose of the company was to own and operate canal sized ships on the Great Lakes, St. Lawrence River and coastal waters. The first three ships of this company were the GLENCADAM and the GLENCLOVA, formerly operated by the Great Lakes Transportation Co. and the 259 foot GLENAFTON built at the Port Arthur Shipbuilding Co. in 1921.<ref>Canadian Railway And Marine World magazine, May 1921</ref> In 1922 Playfair and his associates bought six ships from the French government. All of which had been requisitioned for service overseas during the Great War and all had been built in 1903 at American cities on the Great Lakes and were originally owned owned by the Great Lakes And St. Lawrence Transportation Co. of Chicago. The George C. Howe and John Crerar, built at Chicago, became the GLENEALY and the GLENARNOCH. The H. G. Dalton, built at Superior, Wis., became the GLENDOCHART, J. S. Keefe and Robert Wallace, built at Buffalo, became the GLENFARN and the GLENDOWAN, and the S. N. Parent, built in Detroit, became the GLENARM.<ref>Canadian Railway and Marine World magazine, March 1922</ref> \n\nIn 1926 the 633\u2019 foot GLENMOHR, launched at Midland, was the largest bulk carrier on the Great Lakes.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.woodyboater.com/blog/2015/05/26/argosy-on-the-rocks/ | title=Argosy On the Rocks | accessdate=17 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Other Business interests==\nPlayfair was involved in numerous other activities, among them: \nMidland Towing And Wrecking Co. Ltd.<ref>The Railway And Marine World magazine, February 1906</ref>\nCanadian Dredge And Construction Co. incorporated in 1906<ref>The Railway And Marine World magazine, February 1906</ref>\n[[Maple Leaf Mills Silos|Toronto Elevators]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.maritimehistoryofthegreatlakes.ca/documents/scanner/13/03/default.asp?ID=s009 | title=Ship of the Month No. 97 James B. Eads | publisher=The Scanner | date=December 1980 | accessdate=17 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nThe Georgian Bay Cup was won in 1888 by James Playfair as a prize for the inaugural Georgian Bay Cup Regatta.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.theenterprisebulletin.com/2010/05/05/local-yacht-club-throws-down-sailing-challenge | title=Local yacht club throws down sailing challenge | publisher=Collingwood Enterprise Bulletin | date=May 5, 2010 | accessdate=17 September 2016 | author=WEATHERALL, SHARON}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.simcoe.com/community-story/9481984-collingwood-yacht-club-hosts-the-georgian-bay-cup-race-weekend/ |title=Collingwood Yacht Club Hosts the Georgian Bay Cup Race Weekend |date=2019-07-04 |access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref> The Playfairs also saved Little Lake Park from being cut down in 1906.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.simcoe.com/news-story/5678531-petition-launched-to-save-midland-s-edgehill-park-from-construction/ | title=Petition launched to save Midland's Edgehill Park from construction | publisher=Midland Mirror | date=Jun 16, 2015 | accessdate=17 September 2016 | author=Dunning, Jenni}}</ref> James Playfair purchased a residence and donated it to the Town of Midland for St Andrews Hospital, a predecessor of today's Georgian Bay General Hospital.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://gbgh.on.ca/accountability/our-history/ | title=Our History | publisher=Georgian Bay General Hospital | accessdate=17 September 2016}}</ref> <ref>Canadian Railway And Marine World magazine, June 1918</ref>  On October 25th 1918, Mr. and Mrs. Playfair celebrated their 29th wedding anniversary, with the launching of the WAR FIEND, the first steel cargo ship built at Midland Shipyards. James Playfair was the vice president and general manager of the Midland Shipbuilding Co.<ref>Canadian Railway And Marine World magazine, November 1918</ref> President of Midland Golf And Country Club<ref>Canadian Railway And Marine World magazine,May 1922</ref>The site of Presbyterian church camp Glen Mohr near [[Beaverton, Ontario|Beaverton]] was donated by the Playfairs in 1930.<ref name=\"Glen Mohr\">{{cite web | url=http://gmi.ilovecamp.org/about/history/ | title=A History of Synod Camping | publisher=Cairn | accessdate=17 September 2016}}</ref>  The Playfairs donated their residence, Edgehill, overlooking Midland Harbour on [[Georgian Bay]]. The residence was the first home of the [[Huronia museum]]. Today it is the site of Edgehill Park (formerly known as Huronia Park). \n\nA mural in Midland commemorates Playfair.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.michaeltaylor.ca/culture/midland/playfair.html|title=Michael Taylor|author=Michael Taylor|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=17 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe first cargo ship of the season to arrive in Midland is presented with Playfair's top hat.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.simcoe.com/news-story/2051285-top-hat-a-midland-tradition/ |title=Top hat a Midland tradition |date=May 14, 2012 |work=Midland Mirror|access-date=2018-04-12}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Find a Grave|99410751}}\n*[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1946&dat=19451115&id=4S8rAAAAIBAJ&sjid=OJkFAAAAIBAJ&pg=3629,2354872&hl=en] obituary of Mrs Playfair\n*Huronia Museum archives\n*[http://www.ourmidland.ca/news/parkland/edgehill-park/edgehill-peace-park-visual-history-2015-11-02] Article about Edgehill Park\n*[http://www.shipbuildinghistory.com/history/canadayards/midland.htm] List of ships built at Playfair's shipyard\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Playfair, James}}\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Toronto]]\n[[Category:People from Old Toronto]]\n[[Category:Canadian businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople in timber]]\n[[Category:1937 deaths]]\n[[Category:1860 births]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Scottish descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the Canadian businessperson|the Scottish architect|James Playfair}}\n\n{{infobox person\n|name=James Playfair\n|birth_date=8 July 1860\n|birth_place=[[Toronto]], [[Ontario]]\n|death_date={{death date and age|1937|05|25|1860|9|27|df=y}}\n|death_place=[[Midland, Ontario]], Canada\n|known_for=Great Lakes shipping; Midland businessman\n|occupation=Businessman\n|relations=\n|spouse=Charlotte Ogilivie\n}}\n\n'''James Playfair''' (8 July 1860 \u2013 25 May 1937) was noted for his entrepreneurship in the Great Lakes shipping, lumbering, grain handling, and industrial manufacturing businesses. He was a central figure in the establishment of [[Midland, Ontario]], Canada. The son of John Speirs Playfair (26 June 1826, Glasgow \u2013 2 June 1913, Toronto) and Georgina Hall of Montreal, in 1889 Playfair married Sarah Charlotte Ogilvie (1858-1945), youngest daughter of Senator [[Alexander Walker Ogilvie|A.W. Ogilvie]] of Montreal, former president of Ogilvie Flour Mills.\n\n==Lumbering==\nAt the age of 19, James Playfair was hired by the Toronto Lumber Company which had timber holdings in Simcoe County and mills at Collingwood.<ref>Toronto Marine Historical Society, Scanner, February 1979</ref> The lumbering firm of James Playfair & Company was started in 1884.<ref>The Canada Lumberman magazine, November 1896</ref> Playfair's first mill was located at Sturgeon Bay, (between Waubaushene and Victoria Harbour).<ref>The Canada Lumberman magazine June 15, 1885</ref> In 1894 he formed a lumber partnership with Douglas Leyland White, Jr. and together they purchased the mill formerly known as the [[Andrew Miscampbell|Miscampbell]] mill, at Midland.<ref>The Canada Lumberman magazine, November 1894</ref> D. L. White Jr. of Saginaw, Michigan, was the former treasurer of the Emery Lumber Co. of Saginaw and East Tawas, MI. incorporated in 1885. They were involved in the export of logs from the Sudbury region, to supply their Michigan mills. When the export duty on logs was increased in 1886, the vice president of the Emery Lumber Co. [[Ralph A. Loveland|R. A. Loveland]] arranged to have that firm's Georgian Bay logs manufactured into lumber at Miscampbell's mill.<ref>The Canada Lumberman magazine, October 1887</ref> By the 1890's Andrew Miscampbell desired to devote more of his time to politics. He sold his mill to the Emery Lumber Co. in 1891, but with the reduction of the duty on logs exported to the United States, operations of the Midland mill were abandoned and Emery's lumber production was resumed on the American side.<ref>The Canada Lumberman magazine, May 1891</ref> D. L. White Jr. continued his involvement with the Saginaw Lumber And Salt Company (incorporated in 1881), with the same officers as the Emery Lumber Co.<ref>The Canada Lumberman magazine, February 1893</ref> With their acquisition of the former Emery Lumber Co. mill, James Playfair and D. L. White formed the Playfair-White Company. They contracted to supply the lumber requirements of Saginaw lumberman Arthur Hill, with logs from timber limits the French and Spanish rivers. The mill operated at full capacity until 1916, when the Midland Shipbuilding Company was established on the same site.<ref>Midland on Georgian Bay, (an Illustrated History of Midland, Ontario) by William Northcott and William Smith, published by Huronia Museum, Midland. 2008</ref>\n\n==Shipping Interests==\nIn 1895, Playfair purchased from Burton Bros., of Collingwood, the tug [[Metamora (tug)|METAMORA]], three barges and a large quantity of boom logs, which he planned to use in connection with the lumbering business.<ref>The Canada Lumberman magazine February 1895</ref> In partnership with [[John Waldie]] and Capt. W. H. Featherstonhaugh, Playfair purchased an 11 year old steamer, the W. B. HALL in 1896. The ship was lengthened at the [[Polson Iron Works Limited|Polson Shipyard]] at [[Owen Sound]], renamed ST. ANDREW, and placed in the grain trade between  [[Fort William, Ontario|Fort William]] and [[Goderich, Ontario|Goderich]].<ref>The Midland Navigation Company Limited A Short Corporate History and Vessel Listing, Scanner, v. 11, n. 5, February 1979</ref> The tug, METAMORA and barge ST. ANDREW, were operated by Playfair's Barge And Tug Line.<ref>Official Directory and Atlas of Grand Trunk Railway System 1897-1898</ref> The ST. ANDREW served Playfair for five seasons but, on September 20, 1900, she stranded on an island on [[Lake Superior]] and became a total loss.<ref>Scanner, v. 11, n. 5, February 1979</ref> The METAMORA along with other ships MAGNOLIA, RELIANCE and TRAVELER became part of the Midland Towing And Wrecking Co. Ltd.<ref>The Railway And Marine World magazine, May 1907</ref> The METAMORA struck a shoal at Shawanaga Bay, near Parry Sound in 1907. It subsequently caught fire and was completely destroyed.<ref>The Railway And Marine World magazine, November 1907</ref> \n\nPlayfair incorporated the Midland Navigation Company, in 1901. The Steel bulk carrier MIDLAND QUEEN was built in 1901 at Dundee, Scotland. A second vessel, the MIDLAND KING, was a steel bulk carrier built 1903 at Collingwood by Collingwood Shipbuilding Co. Ltd. The steel bulk carrier MIDLAND PRINCE, was built 1906-07 by Collingwood Shipbuilding Co. EMPRESS OF MIDLAND built in 1907 and the EMPRESS OF FORT WILLIAM built 1908, were steel bulk carriers, both built at Wallsend-on-Tyne by Swan Hunter & Wigham Richardson Ltd. the latter two vessels built for the Midland Navigation Co., but soon became part of the Empress Navigation Co. of Midland.<ref>Scanner, v. 11, n. 5, February 1979</ref>\n\nIn March, 1910, Playfair and Company gained control of the Inland Navigation Company Ltd. from the Mackay brothers, of Hamilton.<ref>Ship of the Month No. 96 WAHCONDAH, Scanner, v. 13, n. 2 November 1980.</ref> A plan was devised to merge the company with the Midland Navigation Co. and the Empress Navigation Co. The ships of the Hamilton firm were: NEEPAWAH, WAHCONDAH, ROSEDALE, GLENELLAH, DUNDEE, DUNELM, WINONA, STRATHCONA, DONNACONA, DUNDURN and STADACONA. The new company was incorporated as Inland Lines Ltd.<ref>The Railway And Marine World magazine, June 1910</ref> \n\nIn mid-January 1911, James Playfair made a bid to purchase the Northern Navigation Co. on behalf of himself and his associates. The offer to purchase the company was subject to approval by the Grand Trunk Railway, concerning a previous arrangement that its president C. M. Hays had made with the company for the construction of a new steamship of the HAMONIC type. The conditions were met and James Playfair became the new president of Northern Navigation Co.<ref>The Railway And Marine World magazine, March 1911</ref> While a merger between the Northern Navigation Co. and Inland Lines Ltd. had been discussed, it was thought that a holding company to control them, was more probable. At that time, there was talk of an even larger merger between the Northern Navigation Co. and the Richelieu And Ontario Navigation Co.<ref>The Railway And Marine World magazine, April 1911.</ref> In 1911 the  Richelieu And Ontario Navigation Co. were allowed to increase their capital stock. At a special meeting of shareholders held on June 26, it was decided to increase the stock from $ 5,000,0000 to $ 10,000,000, with the distribution of new shares to be issued by the directors. The shares of the Northern Navigation Co. Ltd. and of the Inland Lines Ltd. were purchased and paid for with fully paid up stock of the R. And O Navigation Co. Five additional directors were added to the reorganized Richelieu And Ontario Navigation Co. James Playfair became the vice president and managing director.<ref>The Railway And Marine World magazine, July 1911</ref>\n\nOn June 2, 1913, James Playfair was on his way to [[Thunder Bay, Ontario|Port Arthur]], for the launching of the [[SS Noronic|NORONIC]]. He was a passenger on the [[Hamonic (steamship)|HAMONIC]] somewhere on Lake Superior, when the [[wireless]] operator received word that James' father, had passed away in [[Toronto]]. 87 year old John S. Playfair, came to Canada as an employee of dry goods merchant [[John McMurrich]]. For some time John Playfair had managed the firm's Kingston store and may have been involved with shipping on Lake Ontario. He first became involved with [[Alexander Peter Cockburn|A. P. Cockburn]]'s Muskoka Lakes Navigation Co. in 1879 and served as president of that line for more than 25 years. James Playfair transferred to one of the R And O Nav. Co. freighters mid-lake, about 80 miles from [[Sault Ste. Marie, Ontario|Sault Ste. Marie]] and made his way to Toronto by special train.<ref>Canadian Railway And Marine World magazine, July 1913</ref> <ref>Dictionary of Canadian Biography/McMURRICH, JOHN</ref>\n\nA special meeting of the shareholders of Richelieu And Ontario Navigation Co. was held in the company's office in Montreal, on June 19, to ratify an agreement of sale of the company's assets to a new company formed for that purpose. The new company was to be called Canada Transportation Lines Limited.<ref>Canadian Railway And Marine World magazine, July July 1913</ref> In the early part of December it was announced that Canada Transportation Lines would be renamed [[Canada Steamship Lines|Canada Steamship Lines Limited]].<ref>Canadian Railway And Marine World magazine, December 1913</ref> With the acquisition of Inland Lines Ltd. by Canada Transportation Lines, Playfair relinquished personal control of his ships, although he was still a director of the company. James Playfair retired as managing director early in 1914. At Toronto, Playfair was presented with a solid silver center table piece and rose bowl with the following inscription: \"Presented to James Playfair by the officials, staff, captains and engineers of the Inland Lines, Ltd., and Northern Navigation Co., Ltd., as a token of the high esteem in which he is held by one and all.\" An old English chime clock was also presented to Mrs. Playfair.<ref>Canadian Railway And Marine World magazine, March 1914</ref>\n\n==A New Beginning==\nAll aforementioned ships of Inland Lines Ltd. were taken over by the R And O Navigation Co. and absorbed into the new Canada Steamship Lines in 1913. \nIn 1914, Playfair and Company, incorporated the Great Lakes Transportation Company Ltd., to carry on a general navigation business.<ref>Canadian Railway And Marine World magazine, May 1914</ref>  Two of the first ships operated by this firm were the GLENMAVIS and the GLENFOYLE reported to have been built for Playfair interests at [[Derry|Londonderry]], Ireland,<ref>Canadian Railway And Marine World magazine, September and October 1913</ref> Both were owned by James Richardson and Sons, of Kingston Ont. and later operated by Great Lakes Transportation Co. along with the CALGARY built at [[Newcastle upon Tyne|Newcastle]] in 1912.<ref>Maritime History of the Great Lakes website</ref> Playfair soon began to rebuild his own fleet of steamships, from the Pittsburgh Steamship Co. he purchased the WAWATAM, renamed GLENLIVET and from the Chicago and Duluth Transportation Co., came the MINNEKAHTA and MINNETONKA, renamed GLENLYON and GLENFINNAN. The motor vessel TOILER was also acquired, but soon resold.<ref>Canadian Railway And Marine World magazine, April 1914</ref> \n\nThe Glen Transportation Co. Ltd. was incorporated in 1920, the purpose of the company was to own and operate canal sized ships on the Great Lakes, St. Lawrence River and coastal waters. The first three ships of this company were the GLENCADAM and the GLENCLOVA, formerly operated by the Great Lakes Transportation Co. and the 259 foot GLENAFTON built at the Port Arthur Shipbuilding Co. in 1921.<ref>Canadian Railway And Marine World magazine, May 1921</ref> In 1922 Playfair and his associates bought six ships from the French government. All of which had been requisitioned for service overseas during the Great War and all had been built in 1903 at American cities on the Great Lakes and were originally owned owned by the Great Lakes And St. Lawrence Transportation Co. of Chicago. The George C. Howe and John Crerar, built at Chicago, became the GLENEALY and the GLENARNOCH. The H. G. Dalton, built at Superior, Wis., became the GLENDOCHART, J. S. Keefe and Robert Wallace, built at Buffalo, became the GLENFARN and the GLENDOWAN, and the S. N. Parent, built in Detroit, became the GLENARM.<ref>Canadian Railway and Marine World magazine, March 1922</ref> \n\nIn 1926 the 633\u2019 foot GLENMOHR, launched at Midland, was the largest bulk carrier on the Great Lakes.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.woodyboater.com/blog/2015/05/26/argosy-on-the-rocks/ | title=Argosy On the Rocks | accessdate=17 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Other Business interests==\nPlayfair was involved in numerous other activities, among them: \nMidland Towing And Wrecking Co. Ltd.<ref>The Railway And Marine World magazine, February 1906</ref>\nCanadian Dredge And Construction Co. incorporated in 1906<ref>The Railway And Marine World magazine, February 1906</ref>\n[[Maple Leaf Mills Silos|Toronto Elevators]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.maritimehistoryofthegreatlakes.ca/documents/scanner/13/03/default.asp?ID=s009 | title=Ship of the Month No. 97 James B. Eads | publisher=The Scanner | date=December 1980 | accessdate=17 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nThe Georgian Bay Cup was won in 1888 by James Playfair as a prize for the inaugural Georgian Bay Cup Regatta.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.theenterprisebulletin.com/2010/05/05/local-yacht-club-throws-down-sailing-challenge | title=Local yacht club throws down sailing challenge | publisher=Collingwood Enterprise Bulletin | date=May 5, 2010 | accessdate=17 September 2016 | author=WEATHERALL, SHARON}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.simcoe.com/community-story/9481984-collingwood-yacht-club-hosts-the-georgian-bay-cup-race-weekend/ |title=Collingwood Yacht Club Hosts the Georgian Bay Cup Race Weekend |date=2019-07-04 |access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref> The Playfairs also saved Little Lake Park from being cut down in 1906.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.simcoe.com/news-story/5678531-petition-launched-to-save-midland-s-edgehill-park-from-construction/ | title=Petition launched to save Midland's Edgehill Park from construction | publisher=Midland Mirror | date=Jun 16, 2015 | accessdate=17 September 2016 | author=Dunning, Jenni}}</ref> James Playfair purchased a residence and donated it to the Town of Midland for St Andrews Hospital, a predecessor of today's Georgian Bay General Hospital.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://gbgh.on.ca/accountability/our-history/ | title=Our History | publisher=Georgian Bay General Hospital | accessdate=17 September 2016}}</ref> <ref>Canadian Railway And Marine World magazine, June 1918</ref>  On October 25th 1918, Mr. and Mrs. Playfair celebrated their 29th wedding anniversary, with the launching of the WAR FIEND, the first steel cargo ship built at Midland Shipyards. James Playfair was the vice president and general manager of the Midland Shipbuilding Co.<ref>Canadian Railway And Marine World magazine, November 1918</ref> President of of Midland Golf And Country Club<ref>Canadian Railway And Marine World magazine,May 1922</ref>The site of Presbyterian church camp Glen Mohr near [[Beaverton, Ontario|Beaverton]] was donated by the Playfairs in 1930.<ref name=\"Glen Mohr\">{{cite web | url=http://gmi.ilovecamp.org/about/history/ | title=A History of Synod Camping | publisher=Cairn | accessdate=17 September 2016}}</ref>  The Playfairs donated their residence, Edgehill, overlooking Midland Harbour on [[Georgian Bay]]. The residence was the first home of the [[Huronia museum]]. Today it is the site of Edgehill Park (formerly known as Huronia Park). \n\nA mural in Midland commemorates Playfair.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.michaeltaylor.ca/culture/midland/playfair.html|title=Michael Taylor|author=Michael Taylor|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=17 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe first cargo ship of the season to arrive in Midland is presented with Playfair's top hat.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.simcoe.com/news-story/2051285-top-hat-a-midland-tradition/ |title=Top hat a Midland tradition |date=May 14, 2012 |work=Midland Mirror|access-date=2018-04-12}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Find a Grave|99410751}}\n*[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1946&dat=19451115&id=4S8rAAAAIBAJ&sjid=OJkFAAAAIBAJ&pg=3629,2354872&hl=en] obituary of Mrs Playfair\n*Huronia Museum archives\n*[http://www.ourmidland.ca/news/parkland/edgehill-park/edgehill-peace-park-visual-history-2015-11-02] Article about Edgehill Park\n*[http://www.shipbuildinghistory.com/history/canadayards/midland.htm] List of ships b