{"title_page": "Karnan (film)", "text_new": "{{short description|1964 film by B. R. Panthulu}}\n{{distinguish|text=the 1995 film [[Karnaa]]}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2019}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Karnan\n| image          = Karnan poster.jpg\n| alt            = Black and white poster showing Karna (Sivaji), Krishna (NTR), Bhanumati (Savitri), Subhangi (Devika) and Kunti (MV Rajamma)\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[B. R. Panthulu]]\n| producer       = B. R. Panthulu\n| screenplay     = A. S. Nagarajan\n| starring       = [[Sivaji Ganesan]]<br />[[N. T. Rama Rao]]<br />[[Savitri (actress)|Savitri]]<br />[[Devika]]<br />[[M. V. Rajamma]]<br />[[S. A. Ashokan]]<br />[[R. Muthuraman]]\n| music          = [[Viswanathan\u2013Ramamoorthy]]\n| cinematography = V. Ramamurthy\n| editing        = R. Devarajan\n| studio         = Padmini Pictures\n| released       = {{film date|1964|1|14|df=y}}\n| runtime        = 177\u2013180 minutes{{efn|While the film's runtime is listed in ''Encyclopaedia of Indian Cinema'' as 177 minutes,{{sfn|Rajadhyaksha|Willemen|1998|p=380}} the 2012 restored version reviewed by ''[[New Straits Times]]''{{'}} K. Vijayan is 180 minutes.<ref name=\"NST\" />}}\n| country        = India\n| language       = Tamil\n}}\n\n'''''Karnan''''' ({{audio|Ta-\u0b95\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0ba3\u0ba9\u0bcd.ogg|pronunciation}}) is a 1964 Indian [[Tamil language|Tamil-language]] [[List of Hindu mythological or devotional films|Hindu mythological film]] produced and directed by [[B. R. Panthulu]]. It features [[Sivaji Ganesan]] leading an [[ensemble cast]] consisting of [[N. T. Rama Rao]], [[S. A. Ashokan]], [[R. Muthuraman]], [[Devika]], [[Savitri (actress)|Savitri]] and [[M. V. Rajamma]]. The film is based on the story of [[Karna]], a character from the [[Indian epic poetry|Hindu epic]] ''[[Mahabharata]]''.\n\n''Karnan'', which was officially launched in 1963, was shot in palaces at [[Jaipur]] and the war sequences were filmed in [[Kurukshetra]], which featured several soldiers from the [[Indian Army]]. The film's original soundtrack was composed by the duo [[Viswanathan\u2013Ramamoorthy]], while the lyrics were written by [[Kannadasan]]. The screenplay was written by A. S. Nagarajan and the dialogues by [[Sakthi T. K. Krishnasamy]].\n\n''Karnan'' was released on 14 January 1964, during the festival occasion of [[Pongal (festival)|Pongal]]. The film ran for over 100 days in theatres, and later won the [[National Film Award for Best Feature Film in Tamil|Certificate of Merit for the Third Best Feature Film]] at the [[11th National Film Awards]]. It was considered a milestone in Tamil cinema as it brought together the then leading actors of [[Cinema of South India|South Indian cinema]], Ganesan and Rama Rao. The film was also partly responsible for a resurgence in Hindu purana films in the industry. A digitised version of ''Karnan'' was released in March 2012 to critical and commercial success.\n\n== Plot ==\n<!--Find more plot details in these sites: https://jstlikethat.wordpress.com/2012/05/21/karnan/ and http://madhulikaliddle.com/2015/09/05/karnan-1964/-->\nThe unmarried princess [[Kunti]] is seen taking away a small coffin with a baby boy; she earlier got a boon from [[Durvasa]] for her pious service to him. Kunti could invoke a [[mantra]] and be blessed with a child from any male god of her choice. When she tested it playfully, she was blessed by [[Surya|the Sun]] with the baby, which she abandons in the [[Ganges]] to avoid embarrassment. The baby is rescued and adopted by royal charioteer [[Adhiratha]]n, and later named [[Karna]]n.\n\nYears later, Karnan feels heartbroken upon realising that Adhirathan is only his adoptive father. Not wanting to become a charioteer like him, he instead chooses to become a warrior, travels to another kingdom and trains there. Four years later, having mastered archery, Karnan returns home. At the same time, the royal exhibition is held to portray the valour of royal princes, who have just completed education from [[Drona]]chariar. Once there, Karnan challenges the [[Pandava]] prince [[Arjuna]]n in an archery contest, as everyone there hails Arjuna as the best archer ever. Karnan is insulted and refused a chance because of his lowly birth, but the [[Kaurava]] crown prince and cousin of the Pandavas, [[Duryodhana]]n, saves his pride, and crowns Karnan as the king of [[Anga]]. Karnan thus becomes the close friend of Duryodhanan and his wife [[Bhanumati (Mahabharata)|Bhanumati]].\n\nOne day, [[Indra]]n, disguised as a [[Brahmin]], approaches Karnan and asks for his armour and ear ornaments as alms to weaken and prevent him from overpowering Arjuna. Although aware of Indra's intention, Karnan still gives both of the articles that he was born with and which made him invincible. Pleased with Karnan's generosity, Indra gives him a powerful weapon, the ''Nagastra''. Disguised as a Brahmin, Karnan becomes the student of [[Parashurama]]r to acquire the ''[[Brahmastra]]''; Parashuramar eventually realises that Karnan is a [[Kshatriya]], a tribe he opposes. Enraged, he renders Karnan incapable of using the ''Brahmastra'' when most needed, and banishes him.\n\nKarnan later saves princess Subhangi from an uncontrolled chariot; they fall in love and eventually marry. A few years later, [[Krishna]]n, a supporter of the Pandavas, learns about Karnan's true background. He tells Kunti that Karnan is her first-born son. Karnan also learns about his birth later. Kunti meets Karnan and gets two wishes from him, one that he will not attack any of her sons (the Pandavas) except Arjunan during the impending [[Kurukshetra War]], and that he will attack Arjunan with the ''Nagastra'' only once. Karnan refuses to join the Pandavas and remains the friend of their enemy Duryodhanan.\n\nBefore the war begins, Duryodhanan's ministers assemble to appoint the commanders of the army divisions. [[Bhishma]]r is appointed the Commander and he starts nominating generals for different battalions. Karnan is insulted because of his lowly birth and given the command of a low rank infantry. The war begins and in the early days, Bhishma retires and Karnan replaces him. The following day, Karnan goes to war accompanied by his son [[Vrishasena]]n who fights bravely, but is killed by Arjunan.\n\nThe next day, Karnan tries to kill Arjunan with the ''Nagastra'', but Krishnan prevents the weapon from hurting him. Since Karnan cannot use the ''Nagastra'' more than once, he is unable to kill Arjunan. A wheel of his chariot gets stuck in a hole, and he steps down to relieve it. Under Krishnan's direction, Arjunan shoots multiple arrows at Karnan that severely wound him, but Karnan still stays alive. Krishnan tells a shocked Arjunan that the ''[[Dharma]]'' that Karnan performed during his lifetime was protecting his life. Krishnan disguises as a Brahmin, goes to Karnan and asks him his virtues as donation. Karnan generously donates all his virtues to the \"Brahmin\". Arjunan then shoots a few more arrows at Karnan that kill him.\n\nThe Pandavas, who realise that Karnan was their eldest brother, mourn his death. Kunti does the same, while Subhangi dies, traumatised by her husband's death. Arjunan remorses killing Karnan, until Krishnan reveals that the curses by Indran and Parashuramar were also responsible for his death. The film ends with Karnan meeting his father {{mdash}} the Sun {{mdash}} in the [[afterlife]].\n\n== Cast ==\n''Cast according to the opening credits of the film''<ref>{{Cite AV media |title=Karnan |last=Panthulu, B. R. (director) |type=motion picture |language=ta |publisher=Padmini Pictures |year=1964 |place=India |time=4:53 to 5:09 |time-caption=From}}</ref><ref>{{Cite AV media |title=Karnan |last=Panthulu, B. R. (director) |type=motion picture |language=ta |publisher=Padmini Pictures |year=1964 |place=India |time=5:10 to 5:24 |time-caption=From}}</ref>\n{{Col-begin|width=100%}}\n{{col-break|width=20%}}\n* [[Sivaji Ganesan]] as [[Karna]]n\n* [[N. T. Rama Rao]] as [[Krishna]]n\n* [[Savitri (actress)|Savithri Ganesh]] as Duryodhanan's wife, [[Bhanumathi (Mahabharata)|Bhanumathi]]\n* [[Devika]] as Karnan's wife, [[Subhangi]]\n* [[M. V. Rajamma]] as [[Kunti|<!-- don't delink -->Kunti Devi]]\n* [[S. A. Ashokan|Ashokan]] as [[Duryodhana]]n\n* [[R. Muthuraman|Muthuraman]] as [[Arjuna]]n\n* [[O. A. K. Thevar]] as Kanagan\n* [[Javar Seetharaman]] as [[Bhishma]]r\n* [[T. S. Muthaiah|Muthaiah]] as [[Shakuni]]\n* K. Natarajan as Charioteer [[Adhiratha]]n\n* Mustafa as [[Kripa]]chariar\n* Veerasami as [[Drona]]chariar\n* [[R. Balasubramaniam]] as [[Parashurama]]r\n{{col-break|width=20%}}\n* [[V. S. Raghavan]] as [[Vidura]]r\n* [[S. V. Ramadas]] as [[Indra]]n\n* S. A. G. Sami as [[Dhritarashtra]]n\n* Kannan as [[Sanjaya]]n\n* Prem Kumar as [[Yudhishthira|Dharuman]]\n* Sandow Indrajith as [[Bhima]]n\n* Thangaraj as [[Nakula]]n\n* Chinnaiah as [[Sahadeva]]n\n* [[Shanmugasundaram|Shanmuga Sundaram]] as [[Shalya|Shallian]]\n* K. V. Srinivasan as [[Sage (philosophy)|Sage]]\n* [[Master Sridhar]] as [[Indrajit|Meghanathan]]\n* Master Suresh as [[Vrishasena]]n\n* Master Babu as Vrishasenan (first)\n* Prabhakar Reddy as [[Surya]]n\n{{col-break|width=20%}}\n* [[Sobhan Babu]] as [[Chandra]]n\n* Sriram as Iyer\n* [[Samikannu]] as Iyer\n* Stunt Somu as [[Ghatotkacha]]n\n* Pazha. Selva Raj as [[Avanti Kingdom (Mahabharata)|Durmukhan]]\n* [[Kuladeivam Rajagopal]] as [[Kabandha]]n\n* Professor Ramamurthi as the archery expert\n* Sandhya as Kanagan's wife\n* [[Kumari Rukmani|Rukmani]] as Adhirathan's wife, [[Radha (Mah\u0101bh\u0101rata)|Radhai]]\n* [[G. Sakunthala]] as Friend [[Mangala]]\n* [[Jayanthi (actress)|Jayanthi]] as [[Draupadi]]\n* Kalpana as Fairy Goddess\n* Rajeswari as Friend [[Satyavati|Sathyavathi]]\n* K. V. Saroja as Young Kunti\n{{Col-end}}\n\n== Production ==\n=== Development ===\n[[File:Bangalore palace.jpg|thumb|''Karnan'' was the first film to be shot at the [[Bangalore Palace]].]]\n''Karnan'' is based on the life of the character [[Karna]] from the [[Hindu mythology|Hindu]] epic ''[[Mahabharata]]'',<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/Karnan-to-re-release-on-March-16-news-tamil-mdmtxUajdih.html |title=Karnan to re-release on March 16 |date=12 March 2012 |website=[[Sify]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6FQrBMWQ2?url=http://www.sify.com/movies/Karnan-to-re-release-on-March-16-news-tamil-mdmtxUajdih.html |archive-date=27 March 2013 |access-date=3 February 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"NST\" /> and was officially launched in 1963 at Vijaya Studios in [[Chennai]].<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=C. N. R. |date=10 February 1963 |title=The Growing Burden Of Taxation |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y3Y6AQAAIAAJ&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=karnan |magazine=[[The Illustrated Weekly of India]] |volume=84, Part 1 |page=124}}</ref> [[B. R. Panthulu]], who directed and produced the film under the banner Padmini Pictures,<ref name=\"poster\" /> had collected most of his information from scholars [[Kirupanandha Variyar|Kripananda Variar]] and [[Sengalipuram Anantarama Dikshitar|Anantarama Dikshitar]].{{sfn|Arunachalam|1981|p=51}} The film's [[art director]] was Ganga, and the cinematographer was V. Ramamurthy.<ref name=\"RULES\" /> [[Sakthi T. K. Krishnasamy]] wrote the dialogues, and A. S. Nagarajan wrote the screenplay.<ref>{{Cite AV media |title=Karnan |last=Panthulu, B. R. (director) |type=motion picture |language=ta |publisher=Padmini Pictures |year=1964 |place=India |time=4:46 to 4:50 |time-caption=From}}</ref> R. Devarajan was the editor.<ref>{{Cite AV media |title=Karnan |last=Panthulu, B. R. (director) |type=motion picture |language=ta |publisher=Padmini Pictures |year=1964 |place=India |time=5:54}}</ref>\n\n=== Casting ===\n[[Sivaji Ganesan]] was cast in the title role, [[Telugu cinema|Telugu]] actor [[N. T. Rama Rao]] as [[Krishna]]n, and [[R. Muthuraman]] as [[Arjuna]]n.<ref name=\"REDIFF\" /> Actresses [[Devika]] and [[Savitri (actress)|Savitri]] were cast in the female lead roles, and [[S. A. Ashokan]] as Karna's friend [[Duryodhana]]n.<ref name=\"SUGANTH\" /><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-06-15/news-interviews/32253407_1_sandhya-celebration-new-version |title=It's the 100th day celebration for Karnan |date=15 June 2012 |work=The Times of India |access-date=23 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6FQrWFiro?url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-06-15/news-interviews/32253407_1_sandhya-celebration-new-version |archive-date=27 March 2013}}</ref> The role of Karna's mother [[Kunti]] was portrayed by [[M. V. Rajamma]],{{sfn|Rajadhyaksha|Willemen|1998|p=381}} and actress Sandhya played Karna's mother-in-law.<ref name=\"DECCAN\" /> Other supporting cast members included actor [[Shanmugasundaram]] as the charioteer Salliya Chakravarthy, [[V. S. Raghavan]] as [[Vidura|Vidhurar]], actresses Kalpana and [[Jayanthi (actress)|Jayanthi]],<ref name=\"RULES\" /> and the then six-year-old [[Master Sridhar]] as Meganathan, an orphan who meets Karnan after being accused of setting fire to a school.<ref name=\"TECH\" /> Actor K. V. Srinivasan played a minor role as the sage who christens the lead character as Karnan. He also dubbed for the voice of Rama Rao, after Ganesan's insistence with Panthulu.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Rangarajan |first=Malathi |url=http://www.thehindu.com/arts/cinema/article3306963.ece |title=Over to the \u2018voice' |date=12 April 2012 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=8 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6FQjc08Cz?url=http://www.thehindu.com/arts/cinema/article3306963.ece |archive-date=27 March 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Filming ===\n''Karnan'' was filmed with an estimated budget of {{INR}}4&nbsp;million (valued at about US$840 000.84 in 1964).{{efn| name = exchange1948| The exchange rate between 1948 and 1966 was 4.79 Indian rupees ({{INR}}) per 1 US dollar (US$).<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2013-08-24/news/41444029_1_indian-rupee-american-currency-continued-dollar-demand |title=Rupee's journey since Independence: Down by 65 times against dollar |date=24 August 2013 |work=[[The Economic Times]] |access-date=30 August 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130829085318/http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2013-08-24/news/41444029_1_indian-rupee-american-currency-continued-dollar-demand |archive-date=29 August 2013}}</ref>}}<ref name=\"BUDGET\" /> The high cost of the film was attributed to the transportation costs incurred to move [[chariot]]s from Chennai to [[Kurukshetra]], where the war sequences were filmed. Permission from the government was sought, [[cavalry]] and [[infantry]] from the [[Indian Army]] were brought to the locations at Kurukshetra and the first rows of the charging armies on horses and elephants had soldiers from the Indian Army.<ref name=\"UNSUNG\" /> The battle scenes were shot with troupes of the 61 Cavalry Regiment, using 80 elephants, 400 horses and three cameras.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Khajane |first=Muralidhara |url=http://www.hindu.com/fr/2010/07/23/stories/2010072350920300.htm |title=A born showman |date=23 July 2010 |work=The Hindu |access-date=12 March 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130708040739/http://www.hindu.com/fr/2010/07/23/stories/2010072350920300.htm |archive-date=8 July 2013}}</ref> Other scenes were shot at palaces in [[Jaipur]].<ref name=\"UNSUNG\" /> Sridhar finished his long scene in one take, and was paid {{INR}}1000 (valued at about US$210 in 1964{{efn|name=exchange1948}}) for the performance.<ref name=\"TECH\" /> Shooting for ''Karnan'' also took place at the [[Bangalore Palace]] in the [[Cantonment]] area, making it the first film to be shot there.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movie-news-1/mar-12-03/sivaji-ganesan-ramkumar-16-03-12.html |title=When The Maharaja Did Not Want To Meet Sivaji Ganesan |date=16 March 2012 |website=Behindwoods |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6FQNk7TIx?url=http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movie-news-1/mar-12-03/sivaji-ganesan-ramkumar-16-03-12.html |archive-date=27 March 2013 |access-date=12 July 2012}}</ref> In 2012, Panthulu's son Ravishankar revealed that a few shots involving Ganesan and Rama Rao took as many as four days to shoot, because of the large number of personnel involved.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movies-events/Karnan-Trailer-Launch-22-02-12.html |title=Karnan Trailer Launch |website=Behindwoods |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6FQkn17Uo?url=http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movies-events/Karnan-Trailer-Launch-22-02-12.html |archive-date=27 March 2013 |access-date=8 July 2012}}</ref> After the release of ''Karnan'', all the chariots made for the war sequences in Kurukshetra, were donated to the [[Brihadisvara Temple, Thanjavur]].<ref name=\"BUDGET\" /> The film was processed at Filmcenter in Bombay,<ref name=\"poster\" /> and its final length was {{convert|4876|metres|feet}}.<ref>{{Cite magazine |date=11 July 1964 |title=Karnann (Tamil) (Eastman colour) (35&nbsp;mm) (India) |url=https://archive.org/details/in.gazette.central.w.1964-07-11.82327/page/n5 |magazine=[[The Gazette of India]] |page=264}}</ref>\n\n== Music ==\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = Karnan\n| type         = Soundtrack\n| longtype     = to ''Karnan''\n| artist       = [[Viswanathan\u2013Ramamoorthy]]\n| cover        = \n| border       = yes\n| alt          = \n| released     = \n| recorded     = \n| venue        = \n| studio       = \n| genre        = [[Soundtrack|Feature film soundtrack]]\n| length       = \n| language     = [[Tamil language|Tamil]]\n| label        = \n| producer     = {{unbulleted list|M. S. Viswanathan|T. K. Ramamoorthy}}\n| prev_title   = \n| prev_year    = \n| next_title   = \n| next_year    = \n| misc         = {{External media\n | audio1      = {{Youtube|XwFjTOKtc4Q|Official Audio Jukebox}}\n}}\n}}\n\n[[Viswanathan\u2013Ramamoorthy]] (a duo consisting of [[M. S. Viswanathan]] and [[T. K. Ramamoorthy]]) composed the music of ''Karnan'', while the lyrics were written by [[Kannadasan]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.raaga.com/channels/tamil/moviedetail.asp?mid=T0000734 |title=Karnan (1964) |publisher=[[Raaga.com]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130823124615/http://www.raaga.com/channels/tamil/moviedetail.asp?mid=T0000734 |archive-date=23 August 2013 |access-date=6 February 2013}}</ref> The songs were recorded using various instruments like [[Sarangi]], [[Santoor]], [[Shehnai]], [[Dilruba]] and others that were rarely used in Tamil films.<ref name=\"UNSUNG\" /> The songs \"Ullathil Nalla Ullam\" and \"Aayiram Karangal\" were written first and tuned later; for the other songs, Kannadasan wrote lines to fit the tune. He completed all the lyrics for the songs in two days.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Krishnamachari |first=Suganthy |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-fridayreview/his-lyrics-held-a-mirror-to-life/article8944367.ece |title=His lyrics held a mirror to life |date=5 August 2016 |work=The Hindu |access-date=30 August 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160830034841/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-fridayreview/his-lyrics-held-a-mirror-to-life/article8944367.ece |archive-date=30 August 2016}}</ref> The entire soundtrack was completed within three days.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.chennailivenews.com/Entertainment/Movies/20125702105739/Karnan-comes-back-to-win-hearts.aspx |title=\u2018Karnan\u2019 comes back to win hearts |last=Chitra |first=R. |website=Chennai Live News |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130806071938/http://www.chennailivenews.com/Entertainment/Movies/20125702105739/Karnan-comes-back-to-win-hearts.aspx |archive-date=6 August 2013 |access-date=6 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe songs are set in various [[List of Ragas in Hindustani classical music|Hindustani]] and [[Carnatic raga]]s: \"En Uyir Thozhi\" is set in [[Hamir Kalyani]],<ref>{{Cite news |last=Mani |first=Charulatha |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/chennai/chen-columns/the-joy-of-hamirkalyani/article5124087.ece |title=The joy of Hamirkalyani |date=13 September 2013 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=26 March 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160326053503/http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/chennai/chen-columns/the-joy-of-hamirkalyani/article5124087.ece |archive-date=26 March 2016 |author-link=Charulatha Mani}}</ref> \"Maharajan\" in [[Kharaharapriya]],<ref>{{Cite news |last=Mani |first=Charulatha |url=https://www.thehindu.com/features/metroplus/a-ragas-journey-kingly-kharaharapriya/article3310742.ece |title=Kingly Kharaharapriya |date=13 April 2012 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=7 June 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150607085029/http://www.thehindu.com/features/metroplus/a-ragas-journey-kingly-kharaharapriya/article3310742.ece |archive-date=7 June 2015}}</ref> \"Kangal Engey\" in [[Suddha Dhanyasi]],<ref>{{Cite news |last=Mani |first=Charulatha |url=https://www.thehindu.com/features/friday-review/music/a-ragas-journey-soulful-suddhadhanyasi/article2701250.ece |title=A Raga\u2019s Journey&nbsp;\u2014 Soulful Suddhadhanyasi |date=9 December 2011 |work=The Hindu |access-date=26 March 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160326053454/http://www.thehindu.com/features/friday-review/music/a-ragas-journey-soulful-suddhadhanyasi/article2701250.ece |archive-date=26 March 2016}}</ref> \"Iravum Nilavum\" in Shuddha Sarang,<ref>{{Cite news |last=Mani |first=Charulatha |url=https://www.thehindu.com/features/metroplus/call-of-the-swan/article4368746.ece |title=Call of the swan |date=1 February 2013 |work=The Hindu |access-date=26 March 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160326053448/http://www.thehindu.com/features/metroplus/call-of-the-swan/article4368746.ece |archive-date=26 March 2016}}</ref> \"Ullathil Nalla Ullam\" in [[Ahir Bhairav]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://dbsjeyaraj.com/dbsj/archives/42198 |title=\"Mellisai Mannargal\" M.S. Viswanathan and T.K. Ramamurthy, the \u2018Monarchs of Light Music\u2019 in Tamil cinema |last=Jeyaraj |first=D. B. S. |authorlink=D. B. S. Jeyaraj |date=24 July 2015 |website=DBSJeyaraj.com |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161012120009/http://dbsjeyaraj.com/dbsj/archives/42198 |archive-date=12 October 2016 |access-date=12 October 2016}}</ref> \"Poi Vaa Magale\" in [[Anandabhairavi]],<ref>{{Cite news |last=Mani |first=Charulatha |url=https://www.thehindu.com/features/metroplus/a-ragas-journey-the-allure-of-anandabhairavi/article2576822.ece |title=A Raga's Journey&nbsp;\u2013 The allure of Anandabhairavi |date=28 October 2011 |work=The Hindu |access-date=21 October 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161021101458/http://www.thehindu.com/features/metroplus/a-ragas-journey-the-allure-of-anandabhairavi/article2576822.ece |archive-date=21 October 2016}}</ref> \"Kannuku Kulam Yedu\" in Pahadi, and \"Naanichivandhana\" in [[Darbari Kanada]].<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Kumar |first=V. S. |year=2001 |title=The Little-Known Music Of `Karnan' |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QC0qAQAAIAAJ&dq=karnan+panthulu&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22V.+S.+Kumar%22 |magazine=[[Sruti (magazine)|Sruti]]}}</ref>\n\n{{tracklist\n| headline     = Track list\n| extra_column = Singer(s)\n| lyrics_credits=\n| total_length = \n| title1       = En Uyir Thozhi\n| extra1       = [[P. Susheela]]\n| length1      = 3:45\n| title2       = Iravum Nilavum\n| extra2       = [[T. M. Soundararajan]], P. Susheela\n| length2      = 3:47\n| title3       = Kangal Engey\n| extra3       = P. Susheela\n| length3      = 4:53\n| title4       = Kannuku Kulam Yedu\n| extra4       = P. Susheela\n| length4      = 4:09\n| title5       = Maharajan\n| extra5       = T. M. Soundararajan, P. Susheela\n| length5      = 3:22\n| title6       = Mazhai Kodukkum\n| extra6       = Trichy Loganathan\n| length6      = 6:56\n| title7       = Manjal Mugam\n| extra7       = P. Susheela\n| length7      = 4:24\n| title8       = Maranathai Eni\n| extra8       = [[Sirkazhi Govindarajan]]\n| length8      = 3:04\n| title9       = Poi Vaa Magale\n| extra9       = [[Soolamangalam Sisters|Soolamangalam Rajalakshmi]]\n| length9      = 3:44\n| title10      = Ullathil Nalla Ullam\n| extra10      = Sirkazhi Govindarajan\n| length10     = 3:51\n| title11      = Naanichivandhana\n| extra11      = [[Thiruchi Loganathan]]\n| length11     = 1:15\n| title12      = Parithraannaaya\n| extra12      = Sirkazhi Govindarajan\n| length12     = 0:42\n| title13      = Aayiram Karangal Neeti\n| extra13      = T. M. Soundararajan, Sirkazhi Govindarajan, [[Thiruchi Loganathan]], [[P. B. Sreenivas]]\n| length13     = 1:27\n| title14      = Ennakoduppan\n| extra14      = P. B. Sreenivas\n| length14     = 1:31\n| title15      = Malargal Sutti\n| extra15      = P. Susheela\n| length15     = 1:19\n| title16      = Mannavar Porulkalai\n| extra16      = T. M. Soundararajan\n| length16     = 2:47\n| title17      = Nilavum Malarum\n| extra17      = T. M. Soundararajan, P. Susheela\n| length17     = 3:43\n}}\n\n== Release ==\n''Karnan'' was released on 14 January 1964 during the festival occasion of [[Pongal (festival)|Pongal]],<ref name=\"REDIFF\" /> and Ganesan's own [[Shanti Theatre]] in Chennai, which released the film, had a {{convert|60|ft|m}} tall banner of a chariot to attract the audience.<ref name=\"MUGHAL\" /> Ganesan promoted the film by distributing [[Chakarai Pongal]] (sweetened rice) to those who came to Shanti to attend the first screening.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Subramanian |first=Anupama |url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/150721/entertainment-kollywood/article/sivaji-appa-lives-us-through-his-fans-prabhu |title=Sivaji appa lives with us through his fans: Prabhu |date=21 July 2014 |work=[[Deccan Chronicle]] |access-date=7 October 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151007055700/http://www.deccanchronicle.com/150721/entertainment-kollywood/article/sivaji-appa-lives-us-through-his-fans-prabhu |archive-date=7 October 2015}}</ref> The film was dubbed in [[Telugu language|Telugu]] as ''Karna'', and also in [[Hindi]] as ''Dhaan Veer Karna''.{{sfn|Rajadhyaksha|Willemen|1998|p=380}}\n\n== Reception ==\n\n=== Critical reception ===\nThe critic from ''[[The Indian Express]]'' wrote on 17 January 1964, \"Reproducing the incidents from the ''Mahabharatha'', the film has all the aspects demanded by the subject\", adding that Panthulu had not spared any effort to do justice to the theme, and was appreciative of Ganga's art direction and Ramamurthy's cinematography.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=P9oYG7HA76QC&dat=19640117&printsec=frontpage&hl=en |title='Karnan' in colour, opens |date=17 January 1964 |work=[[The Indian Express]] |pages=3}}</ref> The critic from ''[[Ananda Vikatan]]'' wrote that while the film's effort to improve the quality of Tamil cinema quality was praiseworthy, they could not see the dignity of the epic, only the dominance of the extravaganza.<ref>{{Cite magazine |date=c. 1964 |title=\u0b9a\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bbf\u0bae\u0bbe \u0bb5\u0bbf\u0bae\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0b9a\u0ba9\u0bae\u0bcd: \u0b95\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0ba3\u0ba9\u0bcd |magazine=[[Ananda Vikatan]] |language=ta}}</ref> In a review dated 8 February 1964, T. M. Ramachandran of ''[[Sport and Pastime]]'' praised the film's extravaganza but added, \"What fundamentally makes a film truly great is its absorbing presentation without a dull moment. This aspect seems to have been lost sight of by the makers.\"<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Ramachandran |first=T. M. |date=8 February 1964 |title='Karnan' fails to satisfy |url=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.98084/page/n331 |magazine=[[Sport and Pastime]] |volume=18 |page=50}}</ref> Despite being released theatrically in 1964, the film won the [[National Film Award for Best Feature Film in Tamil|Certificate of Merit for the Third Best Feature Film]] at the [[11th National Film Awards]], which honoured films released in 1963.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://dff.nic.in/images/Documents/103_11thNfacatalogue.pdf |title=State Awards for Films |date=25 April 1964 |publisher=[[Directorate of Film Festivals]] |page=25 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190609120223/http://dff.nic.in/images/Documents/103_11thNfacatalogue.pdf |archive-date=9 June 2019 |access-date=9 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Box office ===\nIn its theatrical run, ''Karnan'' completed 100 days in four theatres, including Madurai Thangam (noted as the second largest theatre in [[Asia]] during 1964), and Shanthi. In spite of a successful run after completing 80 days, the film was removed from twelve theatres to allow the release of ''[[Pachai Vilakku (1964 film)|Pachai Vilakku]]'', another Sivaji Ganesan film. At Madurai Thangam, ''Karnan'' earned totally {{INR}}186,805.62 after its 14-week run there.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://i1110.photobucket.com/albums/h452/pammalaar/GEDC5575-1.jpg |title=\u0b95\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0ba3\u0ba9\u0bcd \u0baa\u0b9f\u0bae\u0bcd \u0b95\u0ba3\u0bcd\u0b9f \u0bb5\u0b9a\u0bc2\u0bb2\u0bcd |date=22 April 1964 |publisher=Madurai Thangam |language=Tamil |trans-title=The film Karnan's collections |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6P612efMx?url=http://i1110.photobucket.com/albums/h452/pammalaar/GEDC5575-1.jpg |archive-date=25 April 2014 |access-date=25 April 2014}}</ref> Despite the film running for over 100 days in theatres, critics like [[Baradwaj Rangan]] and ''[[The Times of India]]''<nowiki/>'s M. Suganth state that the film was a box office failure during its release.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Suganth |first=M. |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-07-18/news-interviews/32730051_1_karnan-sivaji-ganesan-chennai-today |title=Karnan to release in the US on July 27 |date=18 July 2012 |work=The Times of India |access-date=16 February 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6FQozF8w2?url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-07-18/news-interviews/32730051_1_karnan-sivaji-ganesan-chennai-today |archive-date=27 March 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Home media ==\n''Karnan'' was released on [[DVD]] by [[Raj Television Network|Raj Video Vision]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.amazon.in/Karnan-Shivaji-Ganesan/dp/B00B9L2JWQ |title=Karnan Tamil dvd with English Subtitles Direct from Manafacturer. |website=[[Amazon.com]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160521044825/http://www.amazon.in/Karnan-Shivaji-Ganesan/dp/B00B9L2JWQ |archive-date=21 May 2016 |access-date=11 March 2013}}</ref> A \"5.1 Channel EDS Sound\" enhanced version was also released by the same company, featuring English subtitles.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/ORIGINAL-ENGLISH-SUBTITLES-COMPLETELY-MANAFACTURER/dp/B00B9L2JWQ |title=Karnan Original Tamil DVD With English Subtitles Completely Boxed And Sealed Direct From {{sic|nolink=y|Manafacturer}} With 5.1 Channel EDS Sound (1964) |website=[[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6hf80PB7D?url=http://www.amazon.com/ORIGINAL-ENGLISH-SUBTITLES-COMPLETELY-MANAFACTURER/dp/B00B9L2JWQ |archive-date=21 May 2016 |access-date=23 March 2013}}</ref> ''Karnan'' is also included alongside various Sivaji Ganesan-starrers in the compilation DVD ''8 Ulaga Adhisayam Sivaji'', which was released in May 2012.<ref>{{Cite news |last=V. Iyer |first=Aruna |url=https://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/for-the-love-of-sivaji/article3412363.ece |title=For the love of Sivaji |date=12 May 2012 |work=The Hindu |access-date=11 March 2013 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6FQo6UhgT?url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/for-the-love-of-sivaji/article3412363.ece |archive-date=27 March 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Re-release ==\n{{Quote box\n| width = 35em\n| align = right\n| quote = ''Karnan'' made a huge impact on me during my childhood. With the help of technology, I wanted to bring the film back to the big screens to give audiences a taste of the movie's grandeur and valuable message ... Most of our films have become so damaged that we will never be able to see them on the big screen. A classic example is ''[[Thillana Mohanambal]]'', whose prints have been totally damaged. I'm happy that I was able to save ''Karnan'' which I'm sure will last for 100 more years after this restoration.\n| source = &nbsp;\u2013 Shanthi Chokkalingam, in an interview with ''[[The Times of India]]''<ref name=\"WINE\" />\n}}\n\nA digitally restored version of ''Karnan'' was released on 16 March 2012,<ref name=\"BORN\" /> to commemorate the birth centenary of Panthulu.<ref name=\"KARNAN CALLING\" /> It is the first Tamil film to be fully digitally restored,<ref name=\"MYTH\" /> costing {{INRConvert|4|m}} and consuming an effort of three years.<ref name=\"MILESTONE\" /> The effort was undertaken by film distributor Shanthi Chokkalingam, who stated, \"The sound negative was totally gone and the five to six reels from the picture negative were damaged to a great extent\".<ref name=\"WINE\" /> Shanthi, who had previously re-released many of M. G. Ramachandran's films, chose to re-release ''Karnan'' because of \"the emphasis it places on friendship and loyalty\".<ref>{{Cite news |last=Srinivasan |first=Meera |url=http://www.thehindu.com/arts/cinema/article2306392.ece |title=\u2018Karnan' set to come back, digitally dazzling |date=30 July 2011 |work=The Hindu |access-date=15 March 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6FQlK3Qji?url=http://www.thehindu.com/arts/cinema/article2306392.ece |archive-date=27 March 2013}}</ref> The digital restoration of ''Karnan'' took place at Sangeetha Sound Studios in Chennai, after a failed attempt with the [[Mumbai]]-based Famous Studios, who earlier restored the 1960 [[Bollywood|Hindi]] film ''[[Mughal-e-Azam]]''.<ref name=\"MUGHAL\" /> Visual improvements and audio restoration were excessively worked upon, with Shanthi stating that the \"biggest challenge was to restore the background score\".<ref name=\"TECH\" /> DVDs were also used to get the sound and music in its original form. To create awareness about the restoration of ''Karnan'', a teaser trailer was launched on 21 February 2012, which received a positive response.<ref name=\"BUDGET\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/digital-trailer-of-sivaji-classic-karnan-launched-news-tamil-mcwjwVbahec.html |title=Digital trailer of Sivaji classic Karnan launched |date=22 February 2012 |website=Sify |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6FQqZR1o3?url=http://www.sify.com/movies/digital-trailer-of-sivaji-classic-karnan-launched-news-tamil-mcwjwVbahec.html |archive-date=27 March 2013 |access-date=8 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe restored version of ''Karnan'' which utilised [[DTS (sound system)|DTS]] [[5.1 surround sound]],<ref name=\"TECH\" /><ref name=\"KARNAN CALLING\" /> was released in 72 screens across [[Tamil Nadu]],<ref name=\"MYTH\" /> and was released by Shanthi's Divya Films.<ref name=\"BORN\" /> It was well received upon release, although M. Suganth called the restoration process \"far from perfect\",<ref name=\"SUGANTH\" /> and Baradwaj Rangan wrote, \"The print occasionally judders, leaving the impression of watching the movie on a screen mounted behind the driver's seat in an auto rickshaw\".<ref name=\"BARADWAJ\" /> Taking a big opening, the film collected roughly {{INRConvert|20|m}} in Chennai within the first few weeks,<ref name=\"BORN\" /> and was later reported to have collected a total of {{INRConvert|50|m}}.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://s501.photobucket.com/user/subbuchennai/media/182127_3856975019591_601342982_n_zps9c4039ac.jpg.html |title=\u0b9a\u0bbf\u0bb5\u0bbe\u0b9c\u0bbf\u0baf\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bcd '\u0b95\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0ba3\u0ba9\u0bcd' \u0bb0\u0bc2. 5 \u0b95\u0bcb\u0b9f\u0bbf \u0bb5\u0b9a\u0bc2\u0bb2\u0bcd |date=16 June 2012 |work=[[Maalai Malar]] |access-date=14 May 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170514171126/http://s501.photobucket.com/user/subbuchennai/media/182127_3856975019591_601342982_n_zps9c4039ac.jpg.html |archive-date=14 May 2017 |language=Tamil |trans-title=Sivaji's ''Karnan'' makes a profit of Rs. 5 crores}}</ref> It had a theatrical run of over 100 days,<ref name=\"DECCAN\" /> and having surpassed what it originally managed to collect in its entire 105-day run at Shanthi theatre, the film was officially declared a commercial success.<ref name=\"BUDGET\" /> Its success soon established a trend of digitising and re-releasing films in Tamil cinema.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Chitra |first=B. |url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/245525/old-favourites.html |title=Old favourites |date=29 April 2012 |work=[[Deccan Herald]] |access-date=12 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6FQoaLDXE?url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/245525/old-favourites.html |archive-date=27 March 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/re-release-is-the-new-trend-in-kollywood-news-tamil-mdxjTwfjghe.html |title=Re- Release is the new trend in Kollywood |date=23 March 2012 |website=Sify |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6FQokjznI?url=http://www.sify.com/movies/re-release-is-the-new-trend-in-kollywood-news-tamil-mdxjTwfjghe.html |archive-date=27 March 2013 |access-date=24 March 2012}}</ref> <!--A 7.1 surround sound version of the film, titled ''Meendum Karnan'', was released on 8 April 2016.<ref>https://tamil.thehindu.com/cinema/tamil-cinema/%E0%AE%9F%E0%AE%BF%E0%AE%9C%E0%AE%BF%E0%AE%9F%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%9F%E0%AE%B2%E0%AF%8D-%E0%AE%AA%E0%AE%B0%E0%AE%BF%E0%AE%AE%E0%AE%BE%E0%AE%A3%E0%AE%A4%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%A4%E0%AE%BF%E0%AE%B2%E0%AF%8D-%E0%AE%95%E0%AE%B0%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%A3%E0%AE%A9%E0%AF%8D-8%E0%AE%AE%E0%AF%8D-%E0%AE%A4%E0%AF%87%E0%AE%A4%E0%AE%BF-%E0%AE%B5%E0%AF%86%E0%AE%B3%E0%AE%BF%E0%AE%AF%E0%AE%BE%E0%AE%95%E0%AE%BF%E0%AE%B1%E0%AE%A4%E0%AF%81/article8429046.ece</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://newstodaynet.com/entertainment/meendum-sivajis-karnan-cinema-halls |title=Archived copy |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160417010757/http://newstodaynet.com/entertainment/meendum-sivajis-karnan-cinema-halls |archive-date=17 April 2016 |access-date=13 April 2016 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>-->\n\n== Legacy ==\n<!-- http://www.thehindu.com/features/metroplus/rajini-kamal-dhanush-cinema-fan-clubs-galore/article7226964.ece -->\n''Karnan'' was considered a milestone in Tamil cinema as it brought together the then leading actors of [[Cinema of South India|South Indian cinema]], Sivaji Ganesan and N. T. Rama Rao.<ref name=\"BORN\" /><ref name=\"MILESTONE\" /> Along with Ganesan's later film ''[[Thiruvilaiyadal]]'' (1965), it was responsible for a resurgence in [[List of Hindu mythological or devotional films|Hindu purana films]], since it was released at a time when Tamil cinema primarily made social films.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/report/slide-show-1-the-most-popular-mythological-films-of-tamil-cinema-south/20140522.htm |title=The Best Mythological Films of Tamil Cinema |last=Saraswathi |first=S. |date=22 May 2014 |website=[[Rediff.com]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://archive.today/20180119070122/http://www.rediff.com/movies/report/slide-show-1-the-most-popular-mythological-films-of-tamil-cinema-south/20140522.htm |archive-date=19 January 2018 |access-date=4 January 2019}}</ref> Actor [[Y. G. Mahendran]] said, \"''Karnan'' can never be remade. Nobody can replace any of the actors of the 1964 classic, and it would amount to mockery if it is done.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/karnan-celebrates-150-days-imagegallery-0-kollywood-mijoT9fgghg.html |title=Karnan celebrates 150 days |website=[[Sify]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6FQMI0tw3?url=http://www.sify.com/movies/karnan-celebrates-150-days-imagegallery-0-kollywood-mijoT9fgghg.html |archive-date=27 March 2013 |access-date=3 February 2013}}</ref> Actor [[Rana Daggubati]], in an interview with Sangeetha Devi Dundoo of ''The Hindu'', said that Ganesan's performances as Kattabomman and Karna served as inspirations for his role in ''[[Baahubali: The Beginning]]'' (2015).<ref>{{Cite news |last=Dundoo |first=Sangeetha Devi |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/friday-review/rana-daggubati-on-a-warrior-mode/article7057707.ece |title=On a warrior mode |date=2 April 2015 |work=The Hindu |access-date=6 April 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150406054346/http://www.thehindu.com/features/friday-review/rana-daggubati-on-a-warrior-mode/article7057707.ece |archive-date=6 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"poster\">{{Cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=P9oYG7HA76QC&dat=19640114&printsec=frontpage&hl=en |title=Karnan |date=14 January 1964 |work=[[The New Indian Express]] |page=14}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"RULES\">{{Cite news |last=Rangarajan |first=Malathi |url=http://www.thehindu.com/arts/cinema/article2999234.ece |title=Karnan rules |date=15 March 2012 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=16 March 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6FQinJ84p?url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/karnan-rules/article2999234.ece |archive-date=27 March 2013}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"REDIFF\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-tamil-film-karnan-completes-150-days/20120807.htm |title=Tamil film Karnan completes 150 days |date=7 August 2012 |website=[[Rediff.com]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https:/